United States changes visa rules
People will have to turn to the Centres of the Visitor Service before the interview at the Consular Department; costs will be lower and the waiting time will be shorter.
From 10 January 2011, the process of negotiating visas at the United States Embassy and consulates has changed.
with a new procedure, most applicants will have to turn to the Centres of the Visa Applicant (shortening from ASC English) before the interview at the Consular Department.
Staff from ASC will receive biometric information from the applicant and will be evaluated by the Consular Department prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages, including the following:
The total costs of the visa will be lower, no more payment will be required for the arrangement of the meeting, the second for processing the application and the other for the delivery of the document by the transport service.
The applicant shall pay only one fee to cover all three services.
The current tariff will remain unchanged: the amount corresponding to $140 for the tourist visa, $150 for visa applications (including visa for temporary workers) and $390 for the visa for traders and investors.
People who want to renew their visa will not have to hold an interview with a consular official, but will only turn to the nearest ASC, where they will present their documents and be fingerprinted.
Given that biometric information will be collected in the ASC, applicants who will require a second interview at the Consular Department will spend a shorter time here than in the past.
Likewise, those who will apply for a visa at the consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay an extra charge of $26.
For further information on the new procedure when applying for a visa, please visit the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boltines/sp101001_Visas-FAQs.html
